Censored Doctors Join Louisiana, Missouri AGs Lawsuit Against Feds for Colluding With Big Tech to Control COVID-19 Narratives

üá∫üá∏@COVID19Up: The number of plaintiffs in a lawsuit alleging the Biden administration colluded with Big Tech to suppress and censor wrongthink on COVID-19 is continuing to grow.

Two of the three authors of the anti-lockdown Great Barrington Declaration, Stanford Medicine health policy professor Jay Bhattacharya and vaccine safety pioneer Martin Kulldorff, have joined the amended lawsuit filed by Louisiana Attorney General Jeff Landry and Missouri AG Eric Schmitt. Also joining them are bioethicist Aaron Kheriaty, who unsuccessfully sued the University of California for firing him for not getting a COVID-19 vaccine, and Jill Hines, co-director of Health Freedom Louisiana and a founder of Reopen Louisiana. All four are clients of the New Civil Liberties Alliance. 

The declaration by Kulldorff, a Harvard professor of 10 years until last fall, recounts his experience as a frequent censorship target during the pandemic.

When then-NIH Director Francis Collins called for a "quick and devastating published take down" of the "fringe epidemiologists" who wrote the Great Barrington Declaration, it spurred "an organized campaign" that slurred and defamed the authors, he said. 

Google "deboost[ed] search results" for the document days after Collins' directive, Facebook removed its page for a week for calling for age- and risk-based vaccine priority, LinkedIn censored posts by Kulldorff, YouTube took down video of his COVID-19 roundtable with Florida Gov. Ron DeSantis, and Twitter sanctioned his account for saying naturally immune people don't need COVID-19 vaccines, masks didn't protect elderly people from SARS-CoV-2, and quoting a black studies professor who wrote about "the historical use of enforced mask use among enslaved populations."

"The most devastating consequence of censoring is ... the reluctance of scientists to openly express and debate scientific questions using their varied scientific expertise," he warned.
